            {
               "text": "### Images from Antropology Peru\n\nThese images are copyright for Antropology Peru and allowed to be used according to the license determined by them.\n\nTo visualize all images, use the left and right arrows on the slide below.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htSlides\"><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">1 / 1</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"img4\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img4', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Andean ceramics from the Formative period. Photo taken on <htcite0>, during a visit to the Museum of Anthropology in Lima, Peru (<htcite0>).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Playing with Consonants and Vowels: An engaging game to help you understand how syllables are formed (<htcite1>).</li><li>Multiplying the Findings: An educational game in which the reader visualizes multiplication while learning about different archaeological sites (<htcite2>).</li><li>Sequence Game (Part I): In this first phase, learning is strengthened by completing numerical sequences that go up to the hundreds, consolidating the understanding of basic fundamentals (<htcite3>).</li><li>Sequence Game (Part II): Continuing the challenge, this phase presents sequences that extend up to billions, deepening the mastery of numerical patterns (<htcite4>).</li></ul></div></div><i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-left htSlidePrev\" onclick=\"htPlusDivs(-1);\"></i><i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-right htSlideNext\" onclick=\"htPlusDivs(1);\"></i></div></p>",
